Wash and dry produce (except cauliflower rice). Trim and thinly slice
@button mushrooms{8%ounce}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating
whites from greens; mince whites. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Place @riced cauliflower{12%ounce} in a medium #microwave-safe bowl{} (use a
large bowl for 4 servings); season with @salt{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4). Cover
bowl with #plastic wrap{} and poke a few holes in wrap. Microwave until tender,
~{5%minutes}. Carefully uncover (watch out for steam!); set aside.

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a large
#pan over medium heat. Add mushrooms and season with @dried thyme{1%tsp}
(1 tsp for 4). Spread into an even layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until
browned and tender, ~{6-8%minutes} (depending on the size of your pan, you
may need to work in batches). Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and a pinch of
@truffle zest{2%g} (you'll use the rest later).

Remove pan from heat. Reserve half the mushrooms in a small #bowl{}, leaving
remaining in pan. Cover bowl with reserved mushrooms with plastic wrap to
keep warm.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan with remaining mushrooms over medium-high heat.
Add scallion whites, garlic, cauliflower rice, and a big pinch of salt; cook,
stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @mushroom stock concentrate{2} and @water{1/2%cup}. Cook, stirring,
until water has mostly absorbed, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to low. Stir in @cream cheese{4%tablespoon}, @sour cream{2%tablespoon}, @butter{2%tablespoon}
(4 TBSP for 4 servings), and remaining truffle zest to taste (we like to use it
all!).

Stir in @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}; season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: If "rice-otto" is too thick, add a splash of water; for an extra-rich
> experience, stir in an additional @?butter{1%TBSP} (2 TBSP for 4).

Divide cauliflower "rice-otto" between #bowls{}. Top with reserved mushrooms
and scallion greens. Serve.